# Policy Pulse RAG ‚Äî Bug Fix Walkthrough

## The Problem

When querying the `sessions` GraphQL endpoint, the response was returning an error because the backend couldn't serialize the response properly.

## Root Cause: GraphQL Schema ‚Üî Java Type Mismatch

The GraphQL schema declares `scrapeDate` and `activatedAt` as **`String`** types:

```graphql
type Session {
  scrapeDate: String!    # ‚Üê String
  activatedAt: String    # ‚Üê String
}
```

But the Java `SessionView` record was returning **`LocalDate`** and **`OffsetDateTime`** objects:

```java
public record SessionView(
    ...
    LocalDate scrapeDate,        // ‚Üê NOT a String
    OffsetDateTime activatedAt   // ‚Üê NOT a String
) {}
```

Spring GraphQL (graphql-java) **cannot auto-coerce** Java date/time objects to the GraphQL `String` scalar. It throws a serialization error like:

> *"Can't serialize value ‚Äî type 'LocalDate' doesn't match expected type 'String'"*

## The Fix (2 files changed)

### 1. [SessionView.java](file:///c:/Users/smart/OneDrive/Desktop/Projects/src/main/java/com/policypulse/graphql/dto/SessionView.java)

Changed both fields from date/time types to `String`:

```diff
 public record SessionView(
         String id,
         int year,
         SessionType sessionType,
         SessionStatus status,
-        LocalDate scrapeDate,
-        OffsetDateTime activatedAt
+        String scrapeDate,
+        String activatedAt
 ) {}
```

### 2. [ChronologyService.java](file:///c:/Users/smart/OneDrive/Desktop/Projects/src/main/java/com/policypulse/chronology/ChronologyService.java#L79-L86)

Updated the mapping code to convert the entity's date/time values to strings:

```diff
 .map(it -> new SessionView(
         String.valueOf(it.getId()),
         it.getYear(),
         it.getSessionType(),
         it.getStatus(),
-        it.getScrapeDate(),
-        it.getActivatedAt()
+        it.getScrapeDate().toString(),
+        it.getActivatedAt() != null ? it.getActivatedAt().toString() : null
 ))
```

